  "prompt": "What function do we use in Java in place of cin>> in C++?",
  "response": "In Java, the equivalent of `cin >>` in C++ for input is typically achieved using the `Scanner` class. Here's how you can use it:\n\n1. First, you need to import the `Scanner` class from the `java.util` package.\n2. Then, you can create an instance of the `Scanner` class to read input from various sources, including standard input (keyboard).\n\nHere is a simple example demonstrating how to use `Scanner` for input in Java:\n\n```java\nimport java.util.Scanner;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        // Create a Scanner object to read input\n        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);\n\n        System.out.print(\"Enter an integer: \");\n        int number = scanner.nextInt();  // Similar to cin >> number in C++\n        \n        System.out.print(\"Enter a string: \");\n        String text = scanner.next();     // Similar to cin >> text in C++\n        \n        System.out.println(\"You entered: \" + number + \" and \" + text);\n\n        // Close the scanner\n        scanner.close();\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, `scanner.nextInt()` reads an integer input, and `scanner.next()` reads a string input, mimicking the behavior of `cin >>` in C++. Remember to close the `Scanner` object with `scanner.close()` when you are done to free resources.",
